# The Principles of Banking — Notes
## Moorad Choudhry (2012, Wiley Finance)
## 1,040 pages, 19 chapters across 5 parts

### Structure
- Part I: A Primer on Banking (Ch 1-4)
- Part II: Bank Asset and Liability Management (Ch 5-11)
- Part III: Bank Liquidity Risk Management (Ch 12-15)
- Part IV: Bank Strategy and Governance (Ch 16-18)
- Part V: Applications Software, Policy Templates (Ch 19)

### Front Matter
- Forewords by John Cummins (Group Treasurer, RBS) and Ian Plenderleith (Former Executive Director, Bank of England)
- Endorsed by Darrell Duffie (Stanford), Carol Alexander (ICMA), K C Chakrabarty (Deputy Governor RBI), Nuno Cassola e Barata (ECB), among many senior banking professionals
- Dedication: wife Lindsay Choudhry
- Epigraph: "Dictum Meum Pactum" — motto of the London Stock Exchange ("My Word Is My Bond")

---

### Forewords
- John Cummins (Group Treasurer, RBS, 29 Sep 2011): Praises Choudhry's rare mix of practical knowledge and academic rigor. Crisis tested widely held assumptions. Book distils ALM jargon into plain English. Highlights need for high-quality liquidity buffers, cash, and highly-rated government bonds. Return to customer deposits and prudent loan-to-deposit ratios — maxims RBS itself was following.
- Ian Plenderleith (Former Exec Director, Bank of England, 31 Mar 2011): Many banks "lost sight of the basic principles of banking." Choudhry calls liquidity "the water of life" of banking. Crisis of 2007-2008 was "as much a crisis of bank liquidity as it was of capital erosion." Wholesale markets expansion let banks economise on liquidity held as a cushion — severe exposure when wholesale funding evaporated. New liquidity requirements are "a turning of the clock back to earlier times, when conservative principles in liquidity management were actually quite common place." Concludes with praise for corporate governance chapter — "a clinical dissection of weaknesses that undermined banks."

### Preface
- Opens with Dune allegory: Fremen on Arrakis called water "the water of life" — for banks, liquidity is the water of life. This is a definition of banking.
- Banking has ancient roots — Babylonians, Roman times. German word "Rechenbank" (counting board) is why we call moneylenders "banks" (Charles Seife, Zero).
- Banks are lifeblood of society. Simon Johnson and James Kwak (13 Bankers): industrialisation requires credit, long-run prosperity requires banks.
- During 2007-2009 crisis, many banks failed spectacularly — managed by people with "monumental incompetence" who had MBA degrees but never obtained professional banking qualifications. "Star bankers" had simply made money in a bull market. Quentin Letts (50 People Who Buggered Up Britain): "They were bull-market innocents caught short by change."
- Book is for SENIOR staff, not beginners. Also for junior staff who want to understand before they reach the Board.
- Companion to earlier book Bank Asset and Liability Management (Wiley, 2007, 1,400 pages) — that one covered product detail, VaR, derivatives pricing. This one focuses on principles, ALM, liquidity management, strategy, governance.
- Chapter 5 (yield curve) kept deliberately technical — "the curve drives everything" — a bank sets the price of its assets and liabilities from its internal risky yield curve.
- Five basic principles of banking:
  1. Secure your funding base (liquidity) for all contingencies BEFORE lending beyond deposit base
  2. Establish sound base of customer deposits; majority of lending funded from core, stable deposits
  3. Lend prudently with sound judgement (not following the herd), diverse range but not outside expertise
  4. Maintain strong capital base of equity, sufficient to absorb all losses including unexpected ones
  5. See (1) — emphasis on liquidity first
- Essential message: CONSERVATISM. Liquidity crises are rare — possible to spend entire career and never experience one. Temptation to relax conservative principles is strong. But banks must survive liquidity crises without taxpayer support.
- Does not review causes of 2007-2009 crash (see The Future of Finance, Wiley 2010). Core of all capital markets: bringing suppliers of capital together with borrowers.
- Quote from Quentin Letts: "The first duty of the high street bank, surely, is stability. To be entrusted with the savings of small-time customers is a heavy responsibility."
- "Liquidity and disciplined ALM are the water of life in banking. That's something the Fremen would have understood."

### About the Author
- Moorad Choudhry: Treasurer, Corporate Banking Division at RBS. Previously Head of Treasury at Europe Arab Bank, Head of Treasury at KBC Financial Products, VP Structured Finance at JPMorgan Chase Bank. Career began at London Stock Exchange in 1989.
- Visiting Professor at London Metropolitan University (Chair of Centre for EMEA Banking, Finance and Economics), Visiting Professor at Brunel University (Mathematical Sciences), Research Fellow at ICMA Centre (University of Reading), Teaching Fellow at Birkbeck (University of London).
- Fellow of CISI, ifs-School of Finance, Global Association of Risk Professionals, Institute of Sales and Marketing Management.
- Managing Editor of International Journal of Monetary Economics and Finance. Editorial boards of Qualitative Research in Financial Markets, Securities and Investment Review, Journal of Structured Finance, American Securitization.
- Leadership quote from Sherif Choudhry (brother, VP CapGemini): "How does one define leadership? Look at the people sitting around you at the Boardroom table. How many of them would follow you to your next job for a cut in pay? If the answer is none of them, then you're not a leader."

