### Chapter 3: Banking and Credit Risk

#### Introduction
- Essence of bank risk management = effective supervision of liquidity risk and credit risk
- Liquidity risk covered in detail in Part III; this chapter = primer on understanding and managing credit risk
- Covers: elements of credit risk exposure, credit risk limit setting policy, loan origination standards, credit ratings (internal and external)

#### Credit Risk Principles
- Credit risk concept is as old as banking itself — but bank management become less aware of it during periods of economic growth, only to reacquaint with its principles after downturns when loan losses increase dramatically
- Evidence of complacency in credit risk management:
  - Credit spreads tightened 1992-1999 and 2002-2007 → blue-chip syndicated loans as low as **10-12 bps** over Libor → to maintain margin, banks increased lending to lower-rated corporates → increased credit risk
  - Investors finding fewer opportunities in IR and FX markets → moved to yield enhancement through lower-rated and emerging market credit assets
  - Rapid expansion of high-yield and EM sectors increased magnitude of credit risk for investors and banks
- Growth in credit risk exposure led to: more sophisticated risk management techniques, rise in corporate defaults and higher losses, demand for credit derivative market, and subsequently structured credit products
- Credit derivatives and structured credit = a response to the rising importance of credit risk management

#### Credit Risk — Two Main Types
1. **Credit default risk**
2. **Credit spread risk**

##### Credit Default Risk
- Risk that issuer of debt (obligor) is unable to meet financial obligations = **default**
- *Technical default*: company has not honoured interest payments for ≥3 months but has not yet reached bankruptcy/administration
- When obligor defaults: lender incurs loss = amount owed minus any recovery amount (from foreclosure, liquidation, restructuring)
- Recovery amount expressed as percentage of total = **recovery rate**
- All portfolios with credit exposure exhibit credit default risk
- Measure of credit default risk = **credit rating** (from Moody's, S&P, Fitch)
- Rating agencies conduct qualitative AND quantitative analysis; factors considered:
  - Financial position of the firm (balance sheet, cash flows, revenues)
  - Firm-specific issues (quality of management, succession planning)
  - Assessment of ability to meet scheduled interest and principal payments (domestic and foreign currencies)
  - Industry outlook, competition, general assessments of domestic economy

##### Table 3.1: Long-term Bond Credit Ratings
| Fitch | Moody's | S&P | Description |
|-------|---------|-----|-------------|
| **Investment Grade — High Creditworthiness** |
| AAA | Aaa | AAA | Gilt-edged, prime, maximum safety, lowest risk |
| AA+/AA/AA- | Aa1/Aa2/Aa3 | AA+/AA/AA- | High-grade, high-credit quality |
| A+/A/A- | A1/A2/A3 | A+/A/A- | Upper medium grade |
| BBB+/BBB/BBB- | Baa1/Baa2/Baa3 | BBB+/BBB/BBB- | Lower medium grade |
| **Speculative — Lower Creditworthiness** |
| BB+/BB/BB- | Ba1/Ba2/Ba3 | BB+/BB/BB- | Low grade; speculative |
| B+/B/B- | B1/B2/B3 | B | Highly speculative |
| **Predominantly Speculative, Substantial Risk or in Default** |
| CCC+ | | CCC+ | Substantial risk, in poor standing |
| CCC | Caa | CCC | May be in default, very speculative |
| CC | Ca | CC | Extremely speculative |
| C | C | C/CI | Income bonds — no interest being paid |
| DDD/DD/D | | D | Default |

##### Credit Spread Risk
- Credit spread = excess premium over government/risk-free risk required by the market for taking on a certain assumed credit exposure
- Figure 3.2: US dollar bond yield curves (May 2009) — shows different credit rating curves (AAA, A, BBB for various sectors: Utility, Industrial, Finance) all above US Treasury Notes/Bills
- Higher credit rating → smaller credit spread; note also higher yields on financial names
- Credit spread risk = risk of financial loss from changes in credit spreads used in MTM of a product
- Exhibited by portfolios where credit spread is traded and MTM; changes in observed credit spreads affect portfolio value → can lead to losses

#### Credit Ratings (detailed)
- Risks of holding fixed interest debt closely connected with issuer's ability to maintain coupon payments and redeem debt at maturity
- Only highest quality government debt and small amount of supra-national debt considered entirely free of credit risk
- Bond yield reflects investors' views on issuer's ability to meet liabilities
- Judgmental analysis of issuer's financial strength and business prospects required
- Large institutional investors employ credit analysis specialists; but too costly to assess every issuer in every debt market
- Two methods for assessing credit risk of debt securities:
  - **Name recognition**: relying on good name/reputation of issuer (e.g., Microsoft, British Petroleum). Barings Bank collapse (1995) showed this is unreliable — Barings had tradition allowing sub-Libor borrowing (on par with highest quality clearing banks), yet collapsed
  - **Formal credit ratings**: ratings from agencies increasingly used for investment decisions about corporate or lesser developed government debt

##### Purpose of Credit Ratings
- Investors accept risk of default on coupon or principal; credit risk generally greater for longer maturity (longer period for issuer to potentially default)
- Even short-dated instruments carry risk (instances of CP default)
- Prospectus/offer document provides information for investors to perform own credit analysis; but credit assessments take time and require specialist skills
- On formal request, credit rating agencies carry out rating exercise on specific debt issue (not the organisation itself — though market commonly refers to "a triple-A company")
- Issuer bears cost of rating; but it is in issuer's interest to request one → raises profile and "saleability" of bonds; investors may refuse to buy unrated paper
- Ratings kept under constant review — if credit quality declines/improves, rating changed accordingly
- Agency may announce it is reviewing a rating (precursor to possible downgrade/upgrade) = putting issue under **credit watch**
  - Usually results in downgrade; during credit watch phase, agency advises caution on current rating
  - Bond price falls as investors sell → upward movement in yield; more pronounced if actual downgrade results
  - Example: October 2008, Ireland placed under credit watch (subsequently lost AAA rating) → immediate sharp sell-off in Irish government Eurobonds before agencies announced actual results

#### Ratings Changes Over Time

##### Ratings Transition Matrix
- Rating agencies constantly review credit quality of rated firms → ratings fluctuate over time
- Moody's and S&P publish historical transition matrices: average rating transition probabilities for each rating class over 1-year period

##### Table 3.2: Moody's 1-Year Rating Transition Matrix (2006)
| From\To | Aaa | Aa | A | Baa | Ba | B | Caa | Default |
|---------|-----|----|----|-----|----|----|-----|---------|
| Aaa | 93.40 | 5.94 | 0.64 | 0.00 | 0.02 | 0.00 | 0.00 | 0.00 |
| Aa | 1.61 | 90.55 | 7.46 | 0.26 | 0.09 | 0.01 | 0.00 | 0.02 |
| A | 0.07 | 2.28 | 92.44 | 4.63 | 0.45 | 0.12 | 0.01 | 0.00 |
| Baa | 0.05 | 0.26 | 5.51 | 88.48 | 4.76 | 0.71 | 0.08 | 0.15 |
| Ba | 0.02 | 0.05 | 0.42 | 5.16 | 86.91 | 5.91 | 0.24 | 1.29 |
| B | 0.00 | 0.04 | 0.13 | 0.54 | 6.35 | 84.22 | 1.91 | 6.81 |
| Caa | 0.00 | 0.00 | 0.00 | 0.62 | 2.05 | 4.08 | 69.20 | 24.06 |

- Some inconsistencies: Aa-rated company has 0.02% default probability — higher than A-rated (0.00%) — explained by scarcity of data for some categories
- Main conclusion: most likely outcome at year-end = rating remains the same
- 1-year transition matrix provides little real value; agencies also publish 5-year and 10-year matrices
- As expected: increased level of default moving down the credit ratings scale
- Figure 3.3: 1-year average cumulative default rates (Moody's, 1985-2006): ranges from near zero for Aaa to ~15.7% for B3
- Figure 3.4: 5-year and 10-year average cumulative default rates show same pattern at higher levels

##### Structured Finance Rating Transitions
- Moody's published Special Comment (March 2009) on structured finance rating transitions 1983-2008
- 12-month downgrade rate for global structured finance: **35.5%** in 2008 (vs 7.4% in 2007, historical)
- Upgrade rate fell from 2.2% to **0.7%** in 2008
- Primary driver: poor performance of most recent structured finance deals sourced from poor-quality US sub-prime mortgage assets
- Table 3.3: Global Structured Finance 12-month Rating Transition Matrix (2008) — vastly worse than corporate finance in 2008 (e.g., Aaa stayed at Aaa only 73.89% of the time vs 95.85% for corporate)
- However, over the longer term (1984-2008 average), structured finance outperformed corporate (e.g., Aaa→Aaa: 97.79% for SF vs 92.76% for corporate)
- Table 3.4: Rating Transition Trends Summary (1983-2008):
  | | SF 2008 | SF 1984-2008 | Corp 2008 | Corp 1984-2008 |
  |---|---|---|---|---|
  | Downgrade rate | 35.50% | 6.25% | 18.22% | 13.47% |
  | Upgrade rate | 0.69% | 2.24% | 4.64% | 9.86% |
  | Avg notches downgraded | 8.30 | 6.99 | 1.64 | 1.78 |
  | Avg notches upgraded | 2.12 | 2.37 | 1.34 | 1.49 |

- Straight corporate credit ratings actually much LESS stable than structured finance ratings, but when changes DO occur, the scale of change is on average LOWER for corporates
- Higher return (on average) of SF securities vs same-rated corporate bonds reflects their higher risk — manifests during extreme bear market situations

#### Understanding Credit Risk
- "Credit risk management is a judgement call. The one single factor that most assists effective credit risk management is knowing one's market."
- Unfamiliarity with a market/customer, or over-reliance on "black box" models → hampers credit risk application, makes it too susceptible to business cycle
- Over-riding principle: understand the market you are operating in. **Never originate loans or invest in assets that one does not understand** — irrespective of sophistication of product or customer
- Complexity of product/transaction does not alter the requirement to understand borrower and its business risks
- Ultimately, credit risk management question = "what is the chance the investment will incur losses, and how much will the lender lose if the borrower is unable to repay? And is the lender able to survive this potential loss?"

#### Definition of Credit Risk
- Risk of loss due to a "credit event" — terminology from credit derivative market
- Credit event can include: outright default (bankruptcy, liquidation, administration), or loss short of full default (e.g., downgrade in credit rating = credit migration)
- In credit derivatives market: range of credit events defined in legal documentation
- In full default: extent of loss can be observed immediately as full notional; but over time, lender typically receives a recovery value from administrators = "recovery value"
- In credit loss event short of default: amount of loss determined by MTM valuation
- **Default definitions** (generally one or more of):
  - Non-payment of interest 90 days after interest-due date
  - Non-payment of loan 90 days after maturity date
  - Restructuring of borrower's loans
  - Filing for bankruptcy, appointment of administrators, liquidation
- Late payment = **NPL (non-performing loan)** or delinquent loan (not defaulted if borrower still in business)
- At some point, NPL will be written off as a default loss — write-down funded out of bank's capital, often at 100% of outstanding notional (even though bank will probably recover a percentage later)
- Alternative definition (Merton, 1974): default occurs when value of company falls below value of its debts — relevant because some models use it as driver for calculating default probability
- Rating agencies generally apply the delay-in-payment definition

#### The Asset Exposure
- Notional/absolute level of risk exposure = first port of call and easiest to calculate
- Given by the amount of loan or investment with the customer/counterparty
- May be fixed ("bullet" loan) or steadily reducing (amortising loan)
- For banking book: vanilla loan stays at notional from origination to maturity
- For tradeable loans/bonds: MTM valuation → exposure amount varies, but should be 100% of notional by maturity
- Figure 3.5: Notional value risk exposure profiles of different product types (bullet loan, amortising loan, LoC, commercial mortgage, project finance loan, credit derivative)
- Trading book assets apply MTM: captures credit migration risk (rating changes affect value)
- Banking book does NOT apply MTM → only captures risk of loss due to default (not migration risk)
- In stressed market conditions: MTM can be self-defeating (falling MTM values → vicious circle of falling prices → impacts confidence → can lead to default itself)
- Asset exposure includes potential future liabilities: LoCs, third-party liquidity lines, other guarantees — off-balance sheet notional amounts also part of credit risk exposure
- Main risk management mechanism for asset exposure = **credit limits** (max amount outstanding to individual customer, industrial sector, country; also by currency)

#### Recovery Value
- Common for banks to write down entire notional value of NPL — but virtually all defaulted assets return an element of recovery value (may take very long time)
- Prudent approach: assign **0% recovery value** for risk management purposes
- Recovery value concept relevant in credit derivative markets — parameter that feeds into pricing

##### Recovery Rates
- Key parameter in credit derivative valuation — unfortunate that an **assumed** rate must be used (actual recovery may not be known for years)
- In cash market: determining RR is long, drawn-out — debt investors queue with all other creditors; process can take months to >10 years
- Rating agencies assume recovery amount from market price of debt asset at time bankruptcy/default announced → approach carried into credit derivative market
- CDS market: recovery defined as market value of the "delivered obligation" — determined by dealer poll bidding for defaulted assets of reference entity
- CDS recovery rates differ from cash market because CDS credit event encompasses circumstances that fall short of full default in the cash market
- Moody's three categories of default for ratings/historical statistics: (1) delayed/failed coupon or principal payments, (2) bankruptcy/receivership, (3) distressed exchange resulting in lower obligation value
- Lesson from 2007-08 credit crunch: when using CDS to hedge credit risk, safest approach = assume **0% recovery rate** (because in default, time passes before recovery received; CDS payment = 100-RR; investor loses gap until recovery received; accountants likely write down entire par value in meantime)
- Despite being key parameter in CDS pricing models, RR doesn't appear to heavily influence CDS premiums in practice — looking at CDS spreads 2000-2004, while "RR" varied widely across industries, CDS premium was fairly similar (Figure 3.6)
- Most industries: BBB CDS levels trading within 10-20 bps of each other; higher-risk industries (computers & electronics, automotive) marked up
- RR in CDS pricing usually set at **40%** (Bloomberg CDSW default); post-crisis more commonly set at **50%**
- Little variation in RR assumption → should have seen greater variation in CDS prices if it were properly accounted for
- **Market-implied default probability approximation** (flat term structure environment): P(default) = CDS spread / [1 - RR]
- Market gives little weight to RR when default probability is low; but during recession/bear market when default probability is higher → this approach becomes risky and can lead to less accuracy in hedging

#### Credit VaR (pp. 221-225)

##### Time Horizon
- Credit VaR typically uses a **1-year risk horizon** — justified because academic and credit agency data are stated annually
- Convenient convention similar to annualised interest rates in money markets
- Risk horizon is adequate as long as it is not shorter than time required to perform risk-mitigating actions
- Figure 3.11: Distribution of bond values showing relative frequencies of all potential migrations (from A rating) — shows peak at "no migration" and distribution across downgrades to B.CCC/Default and upgrades to AA/AAA
- Figure 3.12: Analytics road map for variance-covariance credit VaR (source: JPMorgan RiskMetrics 1997) — three components: Exposures → Compute exposure profile of each asset; Value-at-Risk due to credit → Compute volatility of value caused by up/downgrades and defaults; Correlations → Compute correlations; all feed into Portfolio VaR due to credit events

##### Calculating the Credit VaR
- Three-step methodology for individual and portfolio credit VaR:
  - **Step 1: Exposure Profiles** — incorporates exposure of bonds (fixed/floating), loan commitments, off-balance sheet instruments (swaps). Exposure stated on equivalent basis for all products
  - **Step 2: Volatility of Each Exposure from Up/Downgrades and Defaults** — probability of migration to any other credit rating over the risk horizon is calculated. Each change (migration) results in estimated change in value (from credit spread data and recovery rates). Each value outcome weighted by its likelihood → distribution of value across each credit state → expected value and volatility (standard deviation) calculated
    - Three sub-steps: (1) senior unsecured credit rating determines chance of defaulting/migrating; (2) revaluation at risk horizon by either seniority (recovery rate in default) or forward zero-coupon curve for each rating category; (3) probabilities combined to calculate volatility of value due to credit quality changes
  - **Step 3: Correlations** — individual value distributions combined for portfolio result. Requires estimates of correlation in credit quality changes — difficult to obtain directly from historical data

#### Credit Limit Setting and Rationale (pp. 225-228)
- For commercial banks (especially smaller ones), credit limits and credit exposure are the **most important** aspects of risk management day-to-day
- Smaller banks less likely to be rescued ("not systemically important") → prudent credit risk management culture and through-the-cycle macro-prudential procedures are of primary importance
- Basic principles: **prudence and diversification** — but diversity for its own sake is not good practice; diversify only into sectors where bank has competitive advantage/skill
- Standard textbook approach: capital base drives limit-setting (allocate available capital across business lines). Author argues the **reverse** is better: bank should determine strategy/business model based on risk expertise → this drives the capital level → capital then allocated as credit limits by geography, industry, product

##### Essential Limit-Setting Principles:
1. All single exposures should be sized so that a complete default (with 0% recovery) is contained within existing capital base and doesn't endanger going-concern status
2. Loan portfolio diversified by industrial sector, geography, product line — but within bank's knowledge/expertise
3. Minimum internal (and external) rating criteria established — e.g., "investment-grade only" or "no lending below BB/Ba2"
4. Not lending amounts that over-extend the borrower — "know-your-risk" includes understanding customer's risks (leverage ratio, debt service coverage ratio)
5. Limit categories set to avoid concentration, also by borrower rating
- Ancillary business consideration: policy on whether lending can be a "loss leader" to generate other transaction business, or must create SVA in its own right

##### Credit Limit Setting Process (pp. 228-229)
- Limits set as overlapping by design — captures all categories of risk exposure
- Three limit categories:
  - **Individual obligor**: split by product class, globally and locally. Sub-limits don't necessarily aggregate to overall limit (prevents excess concentration in one product/region). Also set per currency
  - **Geographical region**: split into country limits and sub-regional limits
  - **Industrial sector**: split by sector, sub-limits may not aggregate to overall limit — prevents over-exposure in specific sectors
- No individual limit can be breached — any new capital-using transaction must fit within ALL three limit categories
- **Limit excess** = serious breach of management governance → reported to ALCO (and ExCo if necessary). Corrective actions: (i) cease further business, (ii) transfer exposure via secondary market/securitisation/CDS, (iii) increase the limit, (iv) transfer capacity from elsewhere, (v) asset disposal

#### Loan Origination Process Standards (pp. 229-232)
- Origination process must adhere to principles of prudence and be **"through-the-cycle"** — no reduction in standards during economic growth (avoid bull market over-extension)
- Example of failed approach: Northern Rock, Bradford & Bingley — originated 100% LTV and 125% LTV mortgages plus risky buy-to-let mortgages
- HBOS operated "black box" computer model that delegated approval decision (tick-box credit scoring) — understandable for high-volume but sacrifices "know your customer"

##### Through-the-Cycle Origination Standards:
- **Know your customer**: for one-off/big-ticket = straightforward. For high-volume "black box" systems, danger is bank becomes remote from customers. Acute problem in US, UK, Ireland, Spain 2002-2007 housing boom. Best practice: supplement "black box" with experienced loan analyst review
- **Loan security**: collateral must have sufficient liquidity and value. Genuine liquidity restricted to sovereign liabilities; for other collateral, bank must ensure sufficient margin over loan value
- **Sub-prime lending restrictions**: assets with no/insufficient collateral subject to restrictions (100% LTV, 125% LTV mortgages; self-certified loans)
- Default timing: most common time of default is **45-55 months** after loan start date (not at start or end of loan term). Exception: loans originated at top of economic cycle → default when economy falls into recession
- Default statistics lag actual economy → danger that business continues at lower standards precisely when bank should be more conservative

##### Example 3.1: Credit Scoring (FICO)
- FICO score: developed by Fair Isaac Corporation in 1950s
- Range: **350 to 850** — higher score = lower risk = determines both approval AND interest rate
- Based on: payment history, account balances, types of credit used, length of credit history, new applications
- Factors that do NOT directly influence FICO: income, location, age, occupation, employment history
- What matters: how individual handles bills/credit, length of credit history, how long accounts open, time since last activity
- Bank "black box" mortgage/credit card systems take income/occupation into account but ALSO build FICO-like scores — insufficient risk management on its own, especially during bull markets

#### Credit Process (pp. 232-233)
- Two types of approval process: (i) credit committee; (ii) delegated authority to business line head
- Committee process: ensures proper scrutiny of transactions committing bank's capital. Sponsor = front office business line; committee approves/declines based on risk-reward
- Delegated authority (ii): for high-volume business where committee would be impractical. Risk: "know your risk" principle can be diluted. "Market share" should NOT be a performance indicator — measure performance by genuine shareholder value-added

#### Capital Allocation Process (pp. 233-234)
- "Capital Request Form" example (Figure 3.13) for corporate loan:
  - Facility: Term loan | Currency: USD 500m | Tenor: 5 year | Internal rating: 5 | Recovery rate: 40% | Proposed spread: 200 bps | Risk weighting: 50% | Capital allocated: $25m | Internal funding cost: 80 bps | SVA: $6m
  - Ancillary business expected: FX ($0.1m), FX hedge ($0.5m), underwriting, syndicate, M&A ($0.6m) → Total SVA: $7.1m
- Approval must consider deal economics AND fit within bank's overall strategy/business model
- Key risk elements: (i) anticipated "ancillary business" must be assessed against what is actually received; (ii) underlying transaction should be profitable vs. business line RoC and RoA targets *in its own right*
- Undertaking loss-making transactions to generate subsequent profitable business = tenuous strategy at best

#### Collateral Enablement (pp. 234-235)
- Bank funding models moving toward greater share of **secured funding** → assets should be either repo-able or securitisable
- "Collateral enablement" template: checklist to determine how straightforward it is to later securitise/secure-fund the asset
- Template considerations:
  - **Legal framework**: English law, US law, or other jurisdiction? Some more friendly for securitisation
  - **Transferability**: how easy to transfer loan to another entity/bank? Restrictions on transfer?
  - **Disclosure**: minimum information that must be disclosed to third parties and obligor
  - **Currencies of drawdown**: multi-currency facilities more complex for securitisation
  - **Vanilla or exotic**: fixed coupon/fixed maturity = easier to securitise; exotic features (options, prepayment) = harder
- Customer requirements and strategic objectives take higher priority than collateral enablement, but within that constraint, applying enablement principles is sensible

#### SVA and Credit Strategy (pp. 236-237)
- Since collapse of Bretton Woods and 1980s currency deregulation, bank lending has provided decreasing share of total bank income
- Lending may be the business line with **lowest ROCE** — important to exercise discipline
- Common for banks to treat lending as "loss leader" to create relationships → generate higher value transaction business. If so, aggregate SVA from a client (from ROCE perspective) must be worthwhile; if not, consider withdrawing
- Common error: mistaking **artificial funding profit** for genuine SVA — e.g., "funding arbitrage" (SIVs bought long-dated assets, funded with short-dated CP). When CP market disappeared August 2007, SIVs found to be unsustainable. Bank lending businesses operating similarly risk same fate
- Business lines should aim for **uniformity** in loan origination, execution, documentation — facilitates use of loans as collateral in repo, securitisation, capital relief transactions
- Heterogeneous loan portfolios (different types, jurisdictions, varying notional) much harder to manage for collateral/balance sheet purposes
- Example: 100 bullet loans of same type, same revolving facility, one jurisdiction = much more straightforward than 100 loans in 10 countries, 10 jurisdictions, varying notional

#### Chapter 3 Notes/Bibliography (pp. 238-240)
- Notes reference: Moody's *Structured Finance Rating Transitions: 1983-2008* (March 2009)
- Note 7: FDIC data — 25 US bank failures in 2008, 140 in 2009, 157 in 2010 vs. just 11 in 2003-2007 (except Washington Mutual, these were small/domestic banks that didn't make headlines)
- Author argues: a failed bank in any jurisdiction of any size = gross failure of management and corporate governance. All banks should be treated as systemically important
- Note 8: Self-certified loans generate risk that is difficult to quantify — bank has no real idea of obligor's true income or ability to service/repay
- Bibliography: Choudhry (1999) *An Introduction to Value-at-Risk*; Duffie & Singleton (2003) *Credit Risk*; Kimber (2004) *Credit Risk: From Transaction to Portfolio Management*; Merton (1974) "On the Pricing of Corporate Debt" in *Journal of Finance*

