- Note 1: Par price almost invariably 100%. Some bonds have par defined as 1,000 per 1,000 nominal
- Note 2: "Spot rate" and "zero-coupon rate" used synonymously; technically spot rate is rate of return on single cash flow dealt today and received back almost instantaneously
- Note 4: Credit spread not fixed, fluctuates with market conditions and supply/demand
- Note 6: See Fama (1970) re forward rates and market efficiency
- Note 7: Case Study 5.1 discount function derived from interest-rate data including off-balance sheet derivatives, futures, swaps, and money market deposit rates
- Note 8: Original discussion of unbiased expectations: Lutz (1940) and Fisher (1986)
- Note 16: Recession formally defined as two successive quarters of falling output
- Note 17: UK curve briefly went positive-sloping to 7-8 years in July 1999, quickly reverted; remained inverted until restrictions on institutional investors holding long-dated gilts were lifted by government in 2002
- Note 19: "Strips" = Separate Trading of Registered Interest and Principal of Securities. US Treasury formalised trading in strips in 1985. UK gilt strips trading began December 1997
- Note 22: Shiller (1990) ascribes origin of "forward rate" term to John Hicks in *Value and Capital* (1946)
- Note 27: Campbell et al. (1997), Chapter 10 — excellent, accessible study of term structure; worth purchasing for Ch. 10 alone
- Note 31: "Geo-politics Returns to the Limelight", *Economics Perspectives*, 8 August 2006 (Lloyds Banking Group) — with thanks to Mark Miller
- Note 38: Most appropriate references: Feynman-Kac (1949), Ito (1951), Markowitz (1959), Fama (1965), Black-Scholes (1973) and Merton (1973)
- Note 39: Recent literature on multi-currency curves: Ametrano and Bianchetti (2009), Hagan and West (2006), Kijima Tanaka and Wong (2008), Piterbarg (2010)
- Key references: Adams and Van Deventer (1994), Anderson et al. (1996), Campbell Lo and MacKinlay (1997), Choudhry (2001, 2004a, 2010), Cox Ingersoll and Ross (1985b), Deacon and Derry (1994), Gujarati (1995), Hull (2011), Ingersoll (1946/1977), James and Webber (2000), Jarrow (1996), McCulloch (1971, 1975), Nelson and Siegel (1987), Rubinstein (1999), Shiller (2010), Suits et al. (1978), Sundaresan (1997), Svensson (1994), Van Deventer and Imai (1997), Waggoner (1997)

