## Chapter 13 (continued): Liquidity Risk Metrics (pp. 781-793)

### Surplus Funding Capacity (p. 781)
- Measure of funding capacity remaining after accounting for: headroom needed to survive a stress event (firm-specific or market-wide), extent existing liabilities/assets will roll over, amount of new business put on — over a given period
- Captures the "slack" in the funding base beyond what is required for survival

### Aggregate Limit Metrics (pp. 781-782)
- Liquidity management sets actual limits for specific funding types; level of each limit is a function of risk appetite and liability structure
- Example limits:
  - Wholesale funding < 1 year (unsecured): Max [x] bln
  - Liquidity reserves (cash + central bank eligible securities): Min [x] bln
  - Short-term wholesale funding (total unsecured < 1 year): Max [x] bln
- Composition of short-term vs long-term wholesale funding tracked over time for trend analysis and forecasting
- Banks also set absolute and relative share limits per funding source

### Short-term Wholesale Funding Report — Table 13.11 (p. 782)
- Tracks bank deposits and debt securities (£bln), quarterly actuals + Q1 2011 forecast:
  - Q1 2010: Bank deposits 31.8, Debt securities 48.7
  - Q2 2010: Bank deposits 21.7, Debt securities 51.6
  - Q3 2010: Bank deposits 20.6, Debt securities 51.9
  - Q4 2010: Bank deposits 23.1, Debt securities 51.8
  - Q1 2011 (forecast): Bank deposits 24.5, Debt securities 50.4
- Figures 13.8A/13.8B: stacked bar charts of wholesale liabilities (short-term and long-term), components include money markets, CP, CSA derivatives collateral, equities, securitisation, other (short-term); MTNs, equities, securitisation, other (long-term)

### Cross-border / Foreign Currency Liquidity Risk (p. 783)
- For banks with significant cross-border or foreign currency operations: **do not assume currencies remain transferable in stress** — even normally convertible currencies
- 1997 Asian currency crisis: individual country jurisdictions imposed restrictions on convertibility and outflow of foreign currency deposits
- Cross-border risk must be monitored against separate limits by currency and jurisdiction

### External and Comparative Liquidity Metrics (pp. 783-785)
- Banks do not exist in isolation — proper understanding of own liquidity requires regular review of external indicators and peer group positions
- Treasury department responsible for collating and reporting to ALCO and senior management

#### Market-related Monitoring Tools (p. 783)
- Not an internal metric — BCBS directive to use external market data as proxy early warning indicators for potential liquidity difficulties
- Market-wide indicators: equity prices, debt market yields and spreads (money markets, medium/long-term bonds, derivatives, government bond markets, CDS indices), FX rates
- Bank-specific indicators: equity price, CDS spreads, money-market trading prices, ease of liquidity rollover, bank-specific funding rates by tenor
- Back-testing of market data: e.g. Figure 13.9 shows 3-month Euribor vs 3-month EONIA spread — near-zero pre-Aug 2007, then spike to ~0.8 following 2007 crisis; difficult to spot trend until well into it
- Regulators monitor the same market-wide data

#### Peer-group Comparison (pp. 784-785)
- Figure 13.10: asset-swap spread over 6-month Euribor for peer group banks across tenors (0-10y) — "Bank 1" has no quote beyond 4y maturity, signalling investor concerns about its longer-term health
- **Figure 13.11**: Peer group COF curves constructed using identical interpolation methodology; y-axis = TLP in bps over Libor; Bank 1 has TLP rising to ~500 bps at 5y vs Bank 4 at ~200 bps — stark contrast signals perceived higher risk
- A bank significantly above peer median should reign in asset origination and strengthen liquidity
- Peer group is user-defined: same size, same target customer base, same geography, same credit rating, or "leading group" benchmark setters

### Example 13.1: Strategic and Tactical Liquidity Metrics at a Multi-entity UK Bank (pp. 786-787)
- **Tactical Ratios**:
  1. Maximum Cumulative Outflow (MCO): net cash in/outflow from all on/off-balance sheet items over 14/30/90 calendar days under normal (BAU) conditions
  2. Wholesale Borrowing Limit: maximum Treasury can raise in wholesale/interbank market (including intra-group and custodial funds); must cover all expected short-term liquidity
  3. Swapped Funds Limit: FX liquidity limit for non-domestic funds swapped into local currency
- **Strategic Ratios**:
  1. Advances/Deposits ratio (LTD): corporate + retail loans as % of corporate + retail deposits
  2. Commitments guideline limit: value limit on customer undrawn committed facilities
  3. Medium-term funding ratio: liabilities >1 year maturity / assets >1 year maturity (conceptually similar to NSFR)
  4. Liquid assets ratio: cash + readily marketable securities / total assets
  5. Net inter-bank lending: limit on net inter-bank lending; can be set "always positive" = bank can only ever be net lender to wholesale market, never borrower

### Example 13.2: Specifying the Liquidity Risk Appetite (pp. 787-789)
- Extract from liquidity policy of medium-sized UK commercial bank — Table 13.12
- Key positions:
  - Funding liabilities: £3,950 mm
  - Customer deposits: £1,905 mm (48% of funding — meets >40% target)
  - Private customer deposits: £1,235 mm
  - Liquid currencies: USD, EUR, GBP, JPY, CAD, SEK, NOK, DKK, CHF, AUD, NZD
- Liquidity ratio (maturity mismatch):
  - Regulatory: Sight–8 days >0.00%: actual 13.95%; Sight–1 month >–5.00%: actual 1.66%
  - Internal targets: Sight–8 days >3.00% (target 15.00%); Sight–1 month >0.00% (target 2.00%)
- Maturity transformation:
  - Average asset tenor: 1,192 days
  - Average funding tenor: 39 days (actual 50 days)
  - Transformation ratio: 30x (actual 24x); policy allows < 24x average liability tenor
- Funding source concentration:
  - No single counterparty >10% of funding: largest = 95% (?likely largest sector not single entity); actual 10% = £395 mm — OK
  - No source >25% or £1,000 mm (except private retail): largest = local authority deposits (£670 mm = 17%) — OK
  - Customer deposits >40% of funding: £1,905 mm / £3,950 mm = 48% — met
- FX mismatch: no mismatch >50% of currency volume; no mismatch >£50 mm per currency
- Cash buffer minimum 2% of liabilities: £100 mm = 2% of £3,950 mm — OK (actual £80 mm = 2%)

### Chapter 13 Conclusion (pp. 789-790)
- No "right answer" to how many liquidity metrics a bank should monitor — depends on business model and liability structure
- Key: correct type and number of metrics to produce timely, accurate, reliable MI enabling senior management to understand liquidity position at all times
- Banks do not exist in isolation — a bank can follow an efficient and responsible liquidity policy and still experience stress due to market-wide disruption, country recession, or unpredictable factors
- Liquidity management is as much qualitative as quantitative — finance is a "people" or relationship business
- Key part of ALM and liquidity risk policy: maintain relationships with banks, customers, stakeholders, regulators during normal times — in stressed markets, building relationships is nearly impossible; must be built beforehand

---

## Chapter 14: Liquidity Risk Reporting and Stress Testing (pp. 793-800+)

### Introduction
- Builds on Ch. 13 (measurement); now covers benchmark liquidity risk reporting and stress testing output
- Covers both quantitative and qualitative liquidity reports at aggregate overview level
- Sample reports available as template spreadsheets on Wiley website (see Chapter 19)
- UK FSA regulatory reporting requirements used as benchmark (similar to most other jurisdictions)

### Liquidity Risk Reporting

#### Deposit Tracker Report (pp. 793-800)
- Simple report of current deposit size + forecast going forward; tracked weekly and monthly; key tool for monitoring LTD ratio in short term
- **Table 14.1A**: Deposit tracker report, month-end actuals and year-end forecast (£000s) for medium-sized commercial bank as of May 2009:
  - Deposit categories: Eligible Correspondent Banks, Corporate Client Deposits, Private Bank Client Deposits, Local Authority Deposits, Retail Bank Deposits, Eligible Private Bank Correspondent Banks, Treasury Sales
  - Actuals from 31/12/2008 through 28/05/2009; forecasts through 31/12/2009
  - Total Customer Deposits at 28/05/2009: £2,145,648
  - LTD ratio at 28/05/2009: **86.08%** vs Board-approved limit of **85%** — just exceeding limit; forecast for year-end within limit (LTD declining to ~80.26% by 31/12/2009)
  - The bank must address the LTD breach — either increase deposits or reduce loans
- **Table 14.1B**: Second part — shows how much liabilities must increase OR assets must reduce to meet various LTD targets (80–85%):
  - At LTD 85: liabilities need to increase by £278,851 (31/01) to £303,823 (28/02) etc., OR assets reduce by £237,023 to £258,249 etc.
  - Shows the range of adjustments needed across the forecast period to achieve each target LTD
- **Figure 14.1**: Graphical illustration — stacked bars for customer deposits and loans, line for LTD ratio; actuals from 31/12/08 through May 2009, forecasts through 31/12/09
- **Figures 14.2A/14.2B**: Deposit tracker showing customer deposits by account type and tenor (A) and deposits maturity profile (B)
  - From 14.2A: large % of retail bank deposits are current accounts and rolling deposits, very little fixed-term; for regulatory purposes these treated as short-term liabilities even if local regulator might allow treatment as longer-term based on behavioral analysis
  - Action: bank should undertake marketing exercise to move customers from current/rolling to fixed-term or notice accounts — improves regulatory liquidity metrics
  - Maturity profile by customer type: Retail banking — up to 1 week £1,267.78 mm; Correspondent banks — up to 1 week £549.95 mm; Corporate — £280.45 mm; Local authority — £333.29 mm; Private banking — £109.11 mm

#### Daily Liquidity Report (pp. 799-800)
- Straightforward spreadsheet: liquid and marketable assets + liabilities up to 1-year maturity and beyond
- Provides end-of-day liquidity position for Treasury and Finance; each branch/subsidiary completes one
- **Figure 14.3**: List of liquid securities — input to daily liquidity report
  - Securities and CDs breakdown (ECB eligible vs non-eligible):
    - Bank CDs: non-ECB eligible, liquid at maturity: 231,645
    - Bank CDs: ECB eligible, liquid same day: 0
    - ECB eligible securities, liquid in 1-week tender: 649,967
    - Non-ECB eligible securities, sold over 4 weeks: 277,589
    - Government securities: 9,640
    - Total marketable securities and CDs: 937,196 (securities) + 231,645 (CDs)
  - Non-marketable CDs by remaining tenor (£000s): 2wk=6,645; 1mo=25,000; 2mo=50,000; 3mo=35,000; 6mo=115,000
- **Table 14.2A**: Asset and liability cash flows summary
- **Table 14.2B**: Cumulative liquidity report and liquidity risk factor calculation; "counterbalancing capacity" = sum of available securities to cover sudden cash outflows

