#### Daily Liquidity Report — Table 14.2A and 14.2B (pp. 801-803)
- **Table 14.2A**: Asset and liability cash flows (£000s), London entity, EUR currency, 25-Nov-10
  - Assets breakdown by tenor bucket (1 day through >1 year): Non-marketable securities & CDs, retail call a/c, retail time deposit, inter-group time/call, other bank time/call, corporate time/call, inter-bank
  - Total assets: 3,823,468; average remaining duration of assets: 44.59 months
  - Liabilities breakdown (without stickiness assumptions): retail call/time, inter-group time/call, other bank time, corporate time, undrawn commitments
  - Total liabilities: 4,413,680; average remaining duration of liabilities: 7.72 months
- **Table 14.2B**: Cumulative liquidity report (London, EUR, 25-Nov-10)
  - Cumulative net cash balance: (111,734) 1-day through (2,099,158) 1-year
  - Counterbalancing capacity: 8,676 (1-day) through 1,092,696 (1-year)
  - Liquidity gap: (103,058) to (1,006,462)
  - Liquidity metrics: 1-week ratio 11.13%, 1-month ratio 2.03%, LRF 3.85
  - Limits: 1-week 0.00% (OK), 1-month –5% (OK)
  - Liquidity Risk Factor statistics: average remaining term of assets 44.5900, adjusted for marketable securities 34.8776, average remaining term of liabilities 7.7200, excluding call deposits 8.0046, combined average remaining term 9.0593, LRF 3.8499

#### Funding Maturity Gap ("Mismatch") Report (pp. 803-805)
- Shows maturity gap per time bucket for all assets and liabilities with adjustment for liquid securities; includes cumulative liquidity cash flow; can be combined with daily liquidity report
- **Table 14.3**: Extract from maturity gap report (data as of 2 June 2010, EUR thousands)
  - Liquidity Management – Maturity Mismatch (no behavioural/stress adjustments)
  - Inflows total: (908,203,354) sight; outflows: 893,940,981
  - Net mismatch per bucket: sight (14,262,374), 2-8 days 209,277,716, 9 days–1 month 674,222,290, 1–3 months 875,192,618, 3–6 months 241,699,112 etc.
  - Cumulative mismatch: (1,271,138,655) sight running to (11,311,886,530) total
  - Total adjustments include behavioural adjustment row (Sight–5 Days, Sight–8 Days etc.)
  - Liquidity ratio by bucket: sight 25.16%, 2-8 days 24.36%, 9 days–1 month 8.89%, 1–3 months –11.18%; internal limit 3.00%, –3.00%, 0.00%, 0.00%; FSA limit 0.00%, 0.00%, –5.00%, 0.00%
- **Figure 14.4**: Graphical representation, maturity gap report — stacked bar chart showing cash flows by product type across all tenor buckets from Sight through >5 years
- **Figure 14.5**: Cash flow survival horizon — bank in this example has survival horizon of only **7 days** under normal circumstances; when cash flow value of liquid securities and other adjustments included, extended to **27 days** — still below Basel III requirement; bank must take action to address liquidity shortage

#### Funding Concentration Report (pp. 806-808)
- Key MI for senior Treasury and relationship managers; central principle of liquidity management = **funding diversity**; bank should not be over-reliant on single source or sector; includes intra-group funds
- "Large" depositor = USD50 million or more (or defined as 5% of total liabilities — ALCO rule of thumb)
- **Table 14.4**: Large Depositor Concentration Report Summary — 31 Aug 2010
  - By country: Country A (£1,652,551 = 44.3% of external country funding = 5.0% of group external funding), B (27.0%, 3.6%), C (33.6%, 3.2%), D (10.4%, 2.5%), E (4.7%, 0.4%), F (3.7%, 0.2%), G (4.0%, 0.1%) — Total £4,935,577 = 15.0% of external group funding
  - Large depositors: CBS (£844,101 = 16.5% Bank plc = 14.2% Country A, 2.5% Group), CBL (£588,777), Customer 2 (£448,000), ACO (£341,150) — and 26+ more counterparties
  - CBS = Bank plc's biggest depositor at 16.5% of funding — **exceeds Group's 10% max depositor funding limit** by considerable margin; bank must either increase total liabilities base or risk damaging relationship by asking depositor to remove funds

#### Undrawn Commitment Report (pp. 808-809)
- Off-balance sheet products (liquidity lines, revolving credit facilities, letters of credit, guarantees) = potential stress points for funding requirement
- In stress, customers draw down un-utilised lines as they experience their own funding difficulties — exacerbates bank's funding shortage at exactly the wrong time
- **Figure 14.6A**: Undrawn commitment trend (subsidiary) — head office ~£120-130bn, subsidiary ~£85-100bn, May 2009–Aug 2010
- **Figure 14.6B**: Drawn and undrawn commitment trends — total un-draws + aggregate limit chart
- Aggregate-level reports; bank also produces detailed breakdowns per customer

#### Liability Profile (pp. 809-810)
- Simple breakdown of share of each liability type; example (Figure 14.7) shows categories: customers individuals, repo (highly liquid securities), repo (high-quality securities), asset-backed securities, unsecured other wholesale, repo (other assets), customers large enterprises, conditional liabilities
- In the pie chart example: Customers Individuals 60%, Customers Large enterprises 13%, Repo highly liquid 9%, Repo HQ 9%, remaining categories ~2-3% each
- Additional funding source categories that may appear: covered bonds, client free cash, structured deposit products, unsecured credit institution/governments/non-bank financial, customers SME, group, net derivatives margin, capital (undated/dated), primary issuance

#### Wholesale Pricing and Volume (pp. 810-811)
- Liquidity strength also gauged from funding costs and funding composition by product
- Valuable market intelligence — regulator compiles same information and can spot early warning of funding stress if a bank's funding yield curve rises materially above peer group
- **Figure 14.8**: Firm-specific funding yield curve (EUR) — plots spread over Libor (bps) for cash deposits, primary issuance, covered bonds, ABCP & ABS across tenors 1m–3m through 5y; shows upward slope with primary issuance reaching ~215 bps at 5y
- **Figure 14.9**: Wholesale funding breakdown by product and tenor bucket — outstanding amount EUR; shows heavy concentration in 1-3 month bucket especially for cash deposits and primary issuance

#### Summary and Qualitative Reports (pp. 811-812)
- Liquidity MI for senior management = 1-page summary of key metrics; monthly or as directed by ALCO; frequency may increase during stress period
- "Keeping to one side of A4 will increase the chance that it will actually be read" — important design principle
- **Figure 14.10**: Monthly liquidity snapshot — cumulative liquidity report ($'000) across tenor buckets; liquidity ratios 3-month view (chart of 1-week and 1-month ratios vs limits); key metrics: Liquidity Risk Factor (22.2 vs 25.1 prior month), LTD ratio (96% vs 93%), net inter-group lending (–1,228 vs –1,552)
- **Figure 14.11**: Group Treasury Qualitative Reporting template — monthly liquidity highlights for branches and subsidiaries; 8 key items to address:
  1. Changes in 1-week and 1-month liquidity ratios
  2. Changes to cash and liquidity gap in Cumulative Liquidity model
  3. Changes to Liquidity Risk Factor
  4. Growth or shrinkage of asset books
  5. Changes to inter-group borrowing/lending; counterparties for large deals
  6. Changes in corporate deposits; large dated transactions with confidence level on rollover
  7. Changes in retail deposits
  8. Average daily opening cash position

#### Frequency of Reporting (pp. 812-813)
- Regulator stipulates minimum frequency; ALCO should view as minimum and supplement with additional MI
- **Table 14.5**: UK liquidity reporting requirements for standard ILAS firms:
  - FSA047 (Daily Flows): daily cash flows to 3 months, survival period — BAU: weekly firm-specific/market-wide stress; stress: daily — submission end-of-day Monday (BAU) / end of day following business day (stress)
  - FSA048 (Enhanced mismatch report): ILAS risk drivers + contractual cash flows across full maturity spectrum — same frequency
  - FSA050 (Liquidity Buffer qualifying securities): granular analysis of marketable assets — monthly, 15 business days after month-end
  - FSA051 (Funding concentration): unsecured wholesale borrowings by counterparty class (excludes primary issuance) — monthly, 15 business days
  - FSA052 (Wholesale liabilities): daily transaction prices and volumes for unsecured wholesale liabilities — weekly, end-of-day Tuesday
  - FSA053 (Retail, SME, large enterprises): retail/corporate funding profile + stickiness of retail deposits — quarterly, 15 business days
  - FSA054 (Currency analysis): FX exposures on balance sheet — quarterly, 15 business days
  - Off-balance sheet report: aggregate undrawn committed facilities — monthly, 15 business days

### Stress Test Reports (pp. 813-820)
- Purpose: ascertain extent of funding difficulties in event of idiosyncratic or market-wide stress; output helps senior management take mitigating action
- Primary stress test output = cash flow survival report
- **Figure 14.12A AND B**: Stress test results, cash flow survival horizon
  - Chart A (unstressed): survival horizon = **49 days**
  - Chart B (stressed, taking into account marketable securities sale/repo): survival period extended to **93 days** after accounting for immediate sale/repo of marketable securities
  - FSA-specified stresses applied: wholesale funding, retail liquidity, intra-day liquidity (3- and 5-day), cross-currency liquidity, intra-group liquidity, off-balance sheet liquidity, marketable assets, non-marketable assets, funding concentration
  - Observed Behavioural Forecasting (OBF) assumptions applied:
    - Non-interest bearing liabilities: 100% every 3 days
    - Current accounts: −5.66% every 36 days
    - Retail time deposits: −0.41% every 344 days
    - Capital: 100% every 3 days
    - Cash & equivalents: 100% every 3 days
    - Fiscal liabilities: 100% every 3 days
    - Other time deposits: −0.03% every 47 days
    - Foreign exchange: 100% every 30 days
    - No OBF applied to: corporate deposits, government time deposits, intra-group time deposits, inter-bank time deposits
- **Figure 14.13**: 1-slide PowerPoint summary report for senior management
- **Figure 14.13 (Liquidity Risk Stress Testing Weekly Summary 23 Feb 2010)**:
  - Unstressed cumulative cash flow survival horizon = **42 days**
  - Cash flow survival period beyond that of the 6 months being analysed: reduces by €150mm to €1,113bn
  - Marketable securities: marketable value £1,279,200,226; haircut value £150,114,423; marketable securities stressed £1,129,085,803
  - Shows post-FSA stress cumulative cash flow forecast with OBF applied; stressed cumulative cash flow survival horizon is beyond the start of the 6 months being analysed — i.e. bank is adequately positioned
- Line-by-line stress test result report produced quarterly or as required by regulator (Table 14.6)

