- **Combined shocks**:
  - Slow-burn liquidity crunch: detailed description, Sight–8d: –25.5%, Sight–1mo: –26.7%, Probability: 2%, Impact: 85
  - Severe reputational damage: Sight–8d: –42.4%, Sight–1mo: –51.2%, Probability: 0.50%, Impact: 100
- Report produced quarterly or as required by regulator; produced by Treasury or Risk Management

#### Example 14.1: Treatment of Cash Flows (pp. 826)
- Common liquidity reporting question: treatment of specific cash flow types
- **Non-maturity items** (e.g. demand deposits): treated as 1-day money for regulatory purposes; some regulators allow "behavioural" adjustment if deposits shown to be stable — e.g. 50% allowed as longer term; generally such funds do not improve regulatory liquidity metrics (viewed as 1-day by regulators)
- **Off-balance sheet items** — UK FSA treatment:
  - Derivatives: values/notionals NOT included in liquidity ratio; coupons receivable/payable included on pay dates
  - Commitments: 10% (FSA-specified) of committed but undrawn lending = cash outflow at sight, included in ratio calculations
- **Bank liquidity model treatment**:
  - Derivatives: included to extent collateral payable/receivable under ISDA/CSA agreement; coupons included on pay dates
  - Commitments: all committed but undrawn lending = cash outflow at sight
- Conservative treatment of expected cash outflows (derivative collateral or undrawn commitments) = recommended best practice

---

## Chapter 15: Internal Funds Pricing Policy (pp. 827-840)

### Introduction (pp. 827-829)
- Bank's basic organisation structure: central Treasury manages all borrowing/lending at aggregate level; acts as internal counterparty for funding requirements of all business lines
- **Figure 15.1**: External market → Bank Treasury → (Corporate banking, Retail banking, Private banking/wealth management, Investment banking); two-way internal funding requirement charged at bank's internal funding rate (borrowing and lending)
- Centralising funding removes interest-rate risk and basis risk at business line level; eliminates funding mismatch risk at customer face; these risks centralised and managed by Treasury desk
- Internal funding policy (funds transfer pricing, term liquidity premium, or transfer pricing) = **key driver of capital allocation decision**; must be both rigorous and realistic
- Post-2008 crisis: poor policy setting in build-up reaffirmed importance of this issue; CEBS stated: *"the topic of an effective allocation mechanism for liquidity costs, benefits and risks has come to the fore recently"*
- CEBS (2008, p.147) Recommendation 2: *"Institutions should have in place an adequate internal mechanism — supported where appropriate by a transfer pricing mechanism — which provides appropriate incentives regarding the contribution to liquidity risk of the different business activities. This mechanism should incorporate all costs of liquidity (from short to long term, including contingent risk)."*
- No "one size fits all" policy; chapter discusses one efficacious approach and recommended policy for different product types

### The Concept of Internal Funds Pricing (pp. 829-831)
- Also termed: **funds transfer pricing (FTP)**, **firm liquidity pricing (FLP)**, **term liquidity premium (TLP)**
- Initial post-crash FSA response addressed liquidity standards (self-sufficiency, diversified funding base, longer liability tenor, liquidity buffer) but did NOT address how bank funds managed internally — this was unexpected and subsequently corrected
- Basel Committee and FSA subsequently placed internal funding frameworks under scrutiny; internal funding is a driver of bank business models — shown to be flawed during 2007-2008 crisis

### An Effective Internal Funding Framework (pp. 830-832)
- Internal funding rate = major parameter in business decision-making, driving: sales, asset allocation, product pricing, product approval process, business line performance measurement
- Just as capital allocation must account for cost of regulatory/economic capital, funding decisions carry significant implications for sales/trading teams
- **Ideal**: price at which cash is internally transferred should reflect the true economic cost at each maturity band, and impact on overall bank liquidity
- Any mismatch between asset tenor and funding tenor (after accounting for "repo-ability" of each asset class) should be highlighted and acted upon — reduce reliance on short-term passive funding
- **RoC discipline problem**: business lines ordinarily seek to ensure transactions achieve target RoC; but if different business lines have the same target RoC regardless of risk, required discipline breaks down
- **Uniform cost of funds problem**: even with different RoCs, a uniform COF does not address the different liquidity stresses placed by different asset types; e.g.:
  - 3-month inter-bank loan (very low rollover risk)
  - 3-year floating rate corporate loan fixing quarterly (moderate)
  - 3-year floating rate fixing weekly (higher)
  - 3-year fixed rate loan
  - 10-year floating rate corporate loan fixing monthly
  - 15-year floating rate project finance loan fixing quarterly (highest)
- Each places different liquidity pressures on Treasury funding desk — listed in increasing rollover risk

### Cost of Funds (pp. 832-836)
- **UBS CDO example**: UBS structured credit business funded itself at better-than-market rates (internal bid > LIBID, internal offer < LIBOR — quoted from shareholder report); CDO desk was investing in assets of far lower liquidity than inter-bank assets; no adjustment for tenor mismatch; management viewed more realistic funding model as "constraint on growth strategy"
  - Result: desk reported "super profits" and very high return-on-capital based on artificially low funding costs — encouraged ever more risky decisions
  - Profit was actually **funding arbitrage**: borrowing at low internal rate (reflecting parent bank liquidity/credit profile), investing in illiquid structured finance securities of considerably greater maturity
- **"Fund derivatives" business**: banks lent to hedge fund investors via leveraged structured products with 2+ year maturities (could not be unwound); funded at Libor-flat or Libor+small spread, rolling short-term; liquidity problems became apparent in 2007-2008 when inter-bank liquidity dried up
- **Common pre-crisis approach**: fixed internal funding rate of Libor+15 bps for ALL business lines and ALL tenors — fails to account for differing liquidity profiles
- **Best practice**: adjust basic internal transfer price for the resulting liquidity risk exposure of the business; otherwise risk of excessive risk-taking heavily influenced by artificial funding gain

### Business Best-practice (pp. 833-834)
- Minimum approach: **fixed add-on spread over Libor for term loans/assets >1 year maturity** where coupon re-fix is frequent (monthly/quarterly), to compensate for liquidity mismatch; spread on sliding scale for longer-term assets
- Internal funding discipline as important to risk management as capital buffers and effective liquidity management

### Benchmark Funds Transfer Pricing Policy (pp. 834-836)
- FTP policy should encompass: high-level guidelines on liquidity cost allocation framework + detailed description of funding mechanism for each product type including actual rates by tenor (updated regularly)
- Funding cost passed from Treasury to businesses should include **direct costs** (interest cost of raising funds) AND **indirect costs** (liquidity contingency funding plan and liquidity buffer)
- **CEBS CP36 document**: FTP consists of two components:
  1. Costs of raising funds from ALM perspective and interest rate cost curve (direct costs)
  2. Indirect liquidity costs: (i) mismatch liquidity cost (liquidity tenor, not interest rate tenor, is relevant); (ii) cost of contingent liquidity risk (cost of holding LAB); (iii) other categories (e.g. country risk/capital controls)
- **Author's critique**: Element (i) above would set a 5-year corporate loan funded by rolling 3-month CP at 5-year funding cost — this ignores that banks are in the business of maturity transformation and would rarely undertake matched funding; element (ii) may be passed on as direct cost to business lines — but must be set in line with commercial reality

### Setting the Bank Policy Standard (pp. 835-836)
- Formal internal funding policy objectives:
  1. Ensure consistent liquidity pricing behaviour among business lines
  2. Remove interest-rate risk from the business lines
  3. Include bank's cost of liquidity in product pricing
- Policy should ensure business lines recognise impact of asset/liability pricing on balance sheet and allow for these costs; formalised and approved at ALCO; reviewed semi-annually; review responsibility delegated to Treasury
- Policy should include treatment for each product asset class the bank deals in

### Benchmark FTP Guidelines (pp. 835-840)
- Treasury charges appropriate cost of liquidity to business lines; cost = function of bank's overall COF
- **Two key policy options**:
  1. **Gross vs Net approach**: gross = all assets and liabilities charged/credited with relevant tenor FTP rate from Treasury; net = only net position charged/credited; individual business lines can employ funds they raise themselves
  2. **Marginal vs Actual funding cost**: FTP charge at marginal cost or actual cost of funds
  - **Gross approach at marginal cost** = generally most effective for risk management purposes
- FTP centre = Treasury desk (also market-facing for funding); business lines pay/receive relevant FTP rate by interacting with Treasury
- In a group structure, FTP may be based on more than one pricing curve; one baseline funding curve (bank's unsecured COF curve); Group Treasury passes relevant FTP charge to each operating business; individual businesses may each have different COF (retail bank raises term funds below group marginal COF; investment bank raises at COF but lends below COF; private bank raises behaviorally-long-term funds below COF and lends above COF)
- **Dynamic FTP — Figure 15.2 A–D**:
  - A: Bank running "ALM Smile" — FTP curve set with bank's COF curve
  - B: Funding gap significant at long end — FTP curve set steeper than fair/theoretical COF to incentivise business lines to raise long-term liabilities; penalises term funding gaps at right rate
  - C: Position reversed (surplus of long-term funding) — FTP curve flatter than fair market COF to incentivise correct behaviour
  - D: "Blended" (WACC) FTP rate — shows how much of each business when asset price straddles DCM COF and Retail Bank COF rates
- **Regular review recommended**: at least annually, ideally quarterly; ensures policy remains appropriate for changing market conditions

### Components of the Policy (pp. 838-840)

#### Funds Flow
- Policy states reference rate (Libor or relevant index); rate taken = fix for transaction date
- General rule: assets attract term internal funds rate; all liabilities receive term internal funds rate
- Exceptions on case-by-case basis with Treasury or ALCO sign-off
- Behavioural adjustments may be applied to "sticky" deposits (longer actual maturity than contractual maturity) — cheque accounts, call accounts

#### Liquidity Buffer Cost Allocation
- Cost of preserving liquidity (maintaining LAB including central bank balances) recharged to business lines; reported in monthly management accounts; businesses include in product pricing
- Business lines contributing to bank's liquidity position (e.g. private banking, retail banking) — reduced LAB requirement — receive a credit; recharged (or re-credited) monthly on pro-rata basis based on average liquidity requirements and costs
- Administered by Finance department

#### Regulatory Costs
- Cost of maintaining non-interest-bearing deposits at central bank + supervision fees from national regulator recharged to business lines monthly, pro-rata on average liabilities or other impact on cash balances required
- Funding cost of central bank balance stated in policy — generally reference index rate (1-month or 3-month Libor or Euribor)

#### Bid–Offer Spread
- No strong case for setting bid-offer spread on FTP rates
- Where applied: internal deposits attract bid rate; internal loans charged at offer rate
- Example bid-offer spread table: GBP/EUR 0-1 year: 6 bps; USD/CHF/JPY 0-1 year: 8 bps
- In principle, internal pricing function should operate to zero P&L target; there should be no bid-offer spread; but if dealing both ways, internal funding desk should quote bid and offer; spread should be as small as possible — perhaps 1-2 bps

#### Funds Transfer Pricing Curve (p. 840)
- Actual internal funds curve (also called COF, FTP, or TLP curve) included in policy and reviewed regularly; states rate paid/received by business lines for assets and liabilities across term structure
- **Table 15.1**: FTP pricing curve / grid — Matched funding FTP curve (bps over reference rate):
  - GBP: 0–6mo=0, 6–12mo=5, 1–2yr=15, 3yr=35, 4yr=40, 5yr=50, 6yr=60, 7yr=70, 8yr=80, 9yr=90, 10yr=100, >10yr=135
  - EUR: 0–6mo=0, 6–12mo=5, 1–2yr=10, 3yr=20, 4yr=30, 5yr=40, 6yr=45, 7yr=50, 8yr=55, 9yr=60, 10yr=70, >10yr=90
  - USD: 0–6mo=5, 6–12mo=10, 1–2yr=20, 3yr=40, 4yr=50, 5yr=75, 6yr=85, 7yr=95, 8yr=105, 9yr=110, 10yr=125, >10yr=150
- Table assumes matched funding (rare in practice); positively sloped for each incremental tenor increase — "full marginal cost" pricing; logically tenable but may not be practical commercially
- Assets/liabilities not falling exactly on tenor grids priced by straight-line interpolation
- Final choice of FTP policy = matter of individual bank judgement, decided by ALCO
- **Behavioural analysis**: if term deposit shown 80% sticky at 3 years, the 3-year FTP rate applies to 80% of funds and shorter-term FTP rate to remaining 20%

*Batch 14 complete: pages 821-840.*

---

### Chapter 15 (continued): Internal Funds Pricing Policy (pp. 841-860)

#### FTP Curve — Behavioural Adjustments and Trading Book (pp. 841)
- If call account 50% sticky for 1 year → 1-year FTP rate earned on 50% of funds
- **Trading book assets**: generally assumed liquid, expected to be sold within 6 months; FTP charge set according to **expected holding duration**, not legal maturity
  - Generally at 6-month FTP rate; depends on asset type and liquidity
  - Liquidity tiers: Tier 1 = most liquid (G7 government bonds) → 1-week or 1-month FTP; Tier 3 = least liquid → 6-month internal funds rate
  - Tiers for sovereign/Eurobond assets: Tier 1 = G7 currency bonds; Tier 2 = AUD, CHF, DKK, HKD, NOK, NZD, SEK, SGD bonds; Tier 3 = bonds rated below A–/A3

#### Securitisable Assets (p. 841)
- Assets straightforward to securitise (e.g. prime residential mortgages) have liquidity value precisely because they can be securitised; review on case-by-case basis
- Suggested approach: **50% of relevant tenor FTP rate** (rather than full rate), since asset is partially liquid

#### Specific Product Policy (pp. 842-843)

##### Eurobonds and Sovereign Securities
- Trading book assets: FTP less concerned with legal maturity; assets deemed liquid, held short-term (<1 year); internal funding should reflect true liquidity quality
- Policy classifies securities by perceived liquidity; appropriate TP = average duration of holding (3-month or 6-month)
- Currency FTP grids: most banks only have grids for domestic currency, USD, EUR; convert to other currencies using FX basis swap rate; for hedging may need "quanto" adjustment for FX/correlation factors; one baseline funding curve in reporting currency, convert as required

##### Undrawn Commitments Fee
- FTP for committed facilities = crucial; back-up and liquidity lines drawn at exactly the time bank most wants to preserve liquidity (during funding crisis)
- Until recently: flat standing charge of 10–20 bps; if drawn, fee paid on top of actual borrowing charge; internal charge to business line at or just below customer standing charge
- **Best practice now**: flat minimum internal fee (e.g. **20 bps**), added to depending on facility type and expected usage fluctuation; requires behavioural analysis of product offerings; standing fee + add-on used for new business appraisal and RoC calculation
- **Figure 15.3**: Committed facility usage behaviour profiles:
  - A (Back-up facility): utilisation low normally (~20-25%), spikes to ~80-100% during client-specific stress and market-wide stress — highest risk to liquidity stress position
  - B (Revolving credit facility): regular cyclical utilisation ~35-65%; relatively stable
  - C (Term loan): utilisation builds steadily from 0 to 100% as multiple clients draw over time
- **Table 15.2**: Committed facilities FTP pricing structure (bps):
  - Revolving credit facility: A1/P1 rating → 1yr=20, 2–4yr=20, >5yr=30; A2/P2 → 25, 25, 35
  - Committed back-up line: A1/P1 → 35, 40, 50; A2/P2 → 40, 50, 75
  - Conduit liquidity line: A1/P1 → 35, 40, n/a; A2/P2 → 40, 50, n/a
- Table reviewed semi-annually; grid applies to new business; legal documents state how often bank can revise for existing business

##### Conduit Internal Funding Policy (pp. 845-846)
- Conduits (CP and ABCP) cannot be regarded as completely self-funded; in market-wide liquidity stress, entire conduit liabilities assumed unable to roll in CP market → must be replaced by bank funding
- ABCP conduits: underlying assets rarely match-funded; conduit outstanding balances = large potential liquidity stress position; required funding term = maturity of longest dated asset in conduit
- Standard policy: FTP rate applied at tenor of **longest dated asset** (ABCP conduit) or tenor of **attached liquidity facility** (CP vehicle)

### Funding Management: Derivatives Collateral and Liquidity (pp. 846-860)

#### Funding Impact of Collateralising Derivatives (pp. 847-850)
- Derivatives governed by ISDA agreement; CSA = optional part of ISDA describing how collateral handled between two counterparties
- CSA invariably in place between bank counterparties; less common for corporate and sovereign/central bank counterparties
- Under CSA: party with negative MTM posts collateral to counterparty; usually cash equal to MTM value; sometimes securities
- **Without CSA**: discount curve = bank's cost of funding curve (FTP curve, spread over Libor)
- **With CSA**: discount rate = interest rate applied to collateral posted/received at that time; where only one eligible currency and short-dated derivative → straightforward; multi-currency CSA or long-dated → creates a **collateral option** (counterparty posts cheapest-to-deliver currency/security)
- Standard inter-bank CSA: zero threshold, daily calls; eligible currencies USD, GBP, EUR; OIS/SONIA/EONIA paid on balances respectively
- Pre-2008: difference between OIS and Libor was negligible (avg 10–20 bps); Libor discounting was universal; after 2008: FRA/OIS basis reached **364 bps in USD in October 2008**; OIS-Libor basis for EUR/USD averaged **35–40 bps in 2011** (traded 175 bps at end 2008/early 2009); difference between 3-month and 6-month Libor averaged ~25–30 bps
- **Figure 15.4A**: EUR vanilla IRS rates (vs 6mo Euribor), 29 Dec 2010: 1yr=1.369/1.319, 5yr=2.575/2.525, 10yr=3.388/3.338, 20yr=3.803/3.753, 30yr=3.608/3.558
- **Figure 15.4B**: EUR EONIA swap rates (overnight-index), 29 Dec 2010: 1yr=0.811/0.761, 5yr=2.074/2.004, 10yr=2.963/2.893, 25yr=3.407/3.337, 30yr=3.305/3.235
- Difference between vanilla swap and EONIA swap is material even at short tenors; considerable at long tenors
- **Conclusion**: collateralised derivatives should use **OIS discounting** (not Libor); LCH Clearnet has also adopted OIS discounting
- **Funding sensitivity ("funding delta")**: zero mark-to-market on swap does not mean zero funding delta; in positive-sloping yield curve, fixed-rate payer has net cash outflow at start, gradually shifts to net cash inflow as rates move up
- Rule: use OIS for secured derivatives (under CSA); use bank's COF curve for unsecured derivatives
- Collateral funding requirement should be **termed out** per the "ALM Smile" (not funded wholly short-term)

#### Adjusting Yield Curves (pp. 852-853)
- When CSA allows more than one currency for collateral: collateral poster will choose currency with lowest funding cost (highest return); creates a **collateral option**
- Standard LCH CSA terms: bilateral daily collateral call, zero MTM threshold, cash only, collateral currency = trade currency, overnight rate paid on cash held, overnight curve in trade currency used to discount (EONIA for EUR, OIS for USD, SONIA for GBP)
- Most common inter-bank CSA: allows EUR, USD, GBP cash posting → introduces currency collateral element; cross-currency basis adjustment needed
- **Current practice**: bank constructs **"hybrid" curve** by comparing forward OIS, EONIA, SONIA curves; adjusting for cross-currency basis; taking maximum value at each point in time (i.e. overlying plot of lowest/highest yield along x-axis)

#### Derivatives Funding Policy (pp. 853-860)
- Post-2007/09 crisis: derivatives should be valued/risk-managed recognising differences in funding rates, particularly for uncollateralised derivatives
- **Bank COF splits into four categories**:
  1. Secured short-term funding costs (OIS rate — lowest available; irrelevant for uncollateralised derivatives as positive MTM cannot be used as collateral)
  2. Secured long-term funding costs (covered bonds, MBS)
  3. Short-term unsecured funding costs: bank's COF for 0-12 month tenors (~Libor or spread above)
  4. Long-term unsecured funding costs: bank's COF for 2-10 year tenors (**TLP** — term liquidity premium)
- **Figure 15.5**: OIS, Libor/Swap, and Bank COF curves (spread over 3m Euribor); OIS lowest, Libor middle, Bank COF (TLP) highest and hump-shaped (~5.5% peak at 9-10y, declining for very long tenors)
- First discipline: appropriate funding term structure for collateral posting; terming out proportion of collateral posting funding requirements creates higher cost of business but lower liquidity crisis risk

##### Uncollateralised Derivatives (pp. 854-858)
- Banks deal uncollateralised with customers; hedge in interbank market using collateralised derivatives
- MTM moves: bank either receives collateral from counterparty → Treasury manages as interbank deposit; or posts collateral to counterparty → Treasury borrows as funding requirement
- **Uncollateralised derivative price = Issuer bank zero-coupon bond price × Derivative payoff** (Hull and White (2011))
- Therefore uncollateralised derivative discounted at **higher rate than collateralised** (since bank COF > OIS)
- **Structured notes** (MTN with linked payoff): valued as combination of (i) vanilla term deposit at bank's LT COF; (ii) derivative (IRS or similar) hedged in market with collateralised swap; discounting at appropriate tenor TLP
- CVA formula: CVA = EPE × PD × LGD = EPE × Counterparty Credit Spread
  - Formally: CVA = (1 – R) × ∫₀ᵀ q(t)v(t)dt; discrete: CVA = (1 – R) × Σ qᵢvᵢ
  - where R = recovery rate, q = probability density of counterparty default, v = derivative payoff value
  - DVA = ENE × Credit Spread
  - **Funding Cost = (EPE + ENE) × Derivative Funding Spread**
  - Discounting applied = appropriate tenor bank funding cost
- **Derivative liabilities** (ENE): interest payable should reflect rate paid on bank's bond (counterparty providing term funding); valuing at term COF incorporates DVA — no separate DVA adjustment needed; discount rate = LT COF = TLP
- **Derivative assets** (EPE): conceptually identical to bond issued by counterparty; discount using (i) CVA (counterparty default probability) and (ii) funding cost; hedge = collateralised derivative in interbank market → collateral posting funded by wholesale borrowing at bank's COF; can fund in ST, LT, or mixture
- **Funding assumption matters**: 
  - No easy unwind → fund for full term at LT COF; if funded at ST COF, sudden ST spikes or liquidity squeeze impairs ability to rollover → use LT borrowing, discount at LT COF (TLP)
  - Easy unwind → can apply ST COF (1-year TLP); strong assumption, particularly under stress — high-risk policy
- **Recommendation**: discount derivative asset at TLP; fund collateral postings substantially term; if counterparty default risk ensures contractually long-maturity cash flows, may use secured funding rate (below COF, closer to secured funding curve)
- **Figure 15.7**: Derivatives funding curve as secured funding COF — shows OIS, LIBOR, Bank COF, and Derivatives COF/TLP; Derivatives TLP lies below Bank COF, above Libor for most tenors
- **Derivative Portfolio Maturity**: use contractual maturity or split into tenor buckets using "funding risk per basis point" (FR01) delta ladder; charge appropriate tenor TLP on each bucket
- **Figure 15.8**: Uncollateralised derivatives net position FTP pricing — EPE/ENE by tenor bucket (0-3m, 3-6m, 6-12m, 1-2y, 2-5y, 5-10y, >10y); shows positive EPE in some buckets, negative ENE in others
- **Table 15.3**: Net collateral position report (ALCO liquidity MI): by currency (AUD, CHF, EUR, GBP, USD) × collateral type (Cash, Govt bonds, Corp bonds, ABS/MBS/CDO, LoC, Other); total net collateral = 2,302,661,757; GBP largest (1,474,737,802 dominated by cash 850,155,878)

##### Derivatives Funding Conclusions (p. 860)
- Net impact of uncollateralised derivatives = ongoing unsecured funding requirement
- Should be expected to remain as long as bank is going concern = ordinary business
- Should be funded in LT tenors (with only minority in ST)
- Business best-practice = maximise proportion of LT funding; cost = bank's LT COF (TLP)
- Conclusion: **uncollateralised derivative transactions should be discounted at relevant tenor TLP rate**; portfolio tenor broken down into tenor buckets per derivatives valuation model

#### Example 15.1: Collateral-based Discounting of Interest Rate Swaps (pp. 859-860)

##### Collateral Types and Discount Curves
- ISDA covers three categories: single-currency, multi-currency, uncollateralised derivatives
- Single-currency collateral (e.g. EUR only) → discounted using EONIA curve; USD collateral → FedFunds OIS; multi-currency collateral → hybrid of respective single-currency OIS curves; uncollateralised → bank's COF curve

##### OIS Discounting Background
- Pre-2008: OIS-Libor spread averaged 2–3 bps short-dated, 12–15 bps long-dated; no meaningful market in OIS >1 year; banks paid little attention to difference
- Post-2008: OIS-Libor basis widened considerably; EUR/USD OIS-3mo Libor spread avg 35–40 bps in 2011 (peak ~175 bps late 2008/early 2009); 3mo-6mo Libor spread avg 25–30 bps
- **Simple illustrative example**: Bank A lends Bank B £100 at 5% Libor for 1 year; £105 due in 1 year; discounted at 5% = PV of £100 — tenable for uncollateralised transaction
- Under CSA: collateral posted daily on net MTM → changes the effective discount rate

*Batch 15 complete: pages 841-860.*

---

### Chapter 15 (continued): OIS Discounting Worked Example and CEBS FTP Guidelines (pp. 861-880)

#### Example 15.1 (continued): OIS Discounting Worked Example (pp. 861)
- Under CSA: Bank B posts £100 back to Bank A as collateral immediately; Bank A pays Bank B OIS rate on collateral (4.5%, i.e. 50 bps lower than Libor 5%)
- End of life: Bank B has earned £4.50 on collateral but must pay Bank A £5.00 → Bank B has lost the 50 bps OIS-Libor spread
- Conclusion: trades covered by OIS-based collateral agreement **should be discounted at the OIS rate**; bank must be aware of collateral type allowed in CSA as it significantly impacts portfolio value
- Derivatives portfolio funding must come under the same liquidity management regime as all other liability requirements

#### Example 15.2: CEBS FTP Guidelines (pp. 862-864)
- **Guideline 1**: Liquidity cost benefit allocation mechanism is an important part of the whole liquidity management framework; consistent with governance, risk tolerance, and decision-making framework
  - FTP integral to bank ALM mechanism; as important as maintaining satisfactory funding gap and diverse funds sources; rate at which FTP transacted must be commensurate with correct allocation of costs; each bank should have clearly articulated definition of its risk tolerance re: internal funds pricing
- **Guideline 2**: Liquidity cost benefit allocation mechanism should have proper governance structure supporting it
  - Process "owned" by senior management, delegated to ALCO, with explicit approval and annual review process; internal funding methodology and cost curve applied to liquidity pricing for internal loans and new product appraisals
  - CEBS: *"the area or responsible function ultimately charged with implementing and monitoring the internal prices should be service-oriented and not have a profit target for this specific role. Equally… personnel working within the area should not be set profit targets for this activity."*
  - Easy to follow if Treasury is middle-office/non-P&L function; where Treasury is P&L centre with profit target, FTP setting should be under Finance department; profit from internal funding trades allocated to ALCO book
- **Guideline 3**: Output from the allocation mechanism should be actively and properly used, appropriate to business profiles
  - Liquidity pricing process framed with practical application in mind; applied at "coal face" by transaction managers; rationale understood by everyone
  - "Liquidity pricing methodology should compensate the providers of liquidity and charge the users" — same TLP grid applies to both users of funds and businesses raising liabilities; business line raising long-term funds receives same TLP rate as one that lends funds of same tenor (ignoring bid-offer)
- **Guideline 4**: Scope of application should be comprehensive — covers all significant assets, liabilities, and off-balance sheet items regarding liquidity
  - Retail deposits: fixed-term and call deposits (cheque accounts) are less market-sensitive than wholesale deposits; if bank can show retail call deposit stability >50% over previous 5 years including crisis period → can argue half should be treated as long-term funds; business lines raising retail liabilities should be appropriately rewarded via FTP
  - Committed credit lines: charged at internal rate covering cost of supplying funds should customer draw; set to reflect that these lines are likely drawn at worst possible time (liquidity crisis); similar charge on uncommitted credit lines
  - FTP rates reviewed regularly, should reflect current market conditions and bank's funding position; CEBS: should reflect direct and indirect funding costs including cost of liquidity buffer; author's view: cost of LAB can be recharged pro-rata to business lines as separate distinct fee, not incorporated in FTP curve
- **Guideline 5**: Internal prices should be determined by robust methodologies, taking into account the various factors involved in liquidity risk
  - Bank sets internal curve with respect to market (Libor or Euribor); for >1-year tenors, refers to swap curve; bank should note its own-name CDS curve; if no secondary market debt for certain tenors, construct using term structure model with proxy rate inputs
  - Key post-crash issue: OIS rate paid on collateral under derivative contract CSA is different to Libor — must be taken into account in liquidity and funding policy
  - Bank's funding rate includes both liquidity premium AND name-specific credit risk; challenge is extracting liquidity element from credit risk element
  - Fundamental principle: product/business line approval process should be closely integrated with internal pricing process; "selling only fairly priced products can be considered a major criterion for the long-term functioning of an institution" (CEBS)

### Pricing Liquidity (pp. 864-868)

#### The Concept of the Term Liquidity Premium (pp. 865-868)
- **Match-funded base case**: if bank always borrows at Libor-flat and lends on matched-funded basis → no TLP needed (FTP = 0); e.g. 5-year corporate loan floating quarterly at +250 bps / 5-year FRN paying Libor-flat → liquidity stress negated; Treasury charges Corporate Banking Libor-flat; Corporate Banking uses full 250 bps net profit for RoC calculation
- **Mismatched case**: 5-year corporate loan / 3-month inter-bank deposit rolling quarterly → liquidity stress NOT alleviated; bank must continuously roll over funding for 5 years; unknown if always able to roll
  - Treasury must set liquidity premium on internal loan; otherwise Corporate Banking continues using 250 bps net profit for RoC — this will be over-stated, incorporating funding spread gain that is not real; SVA over-stated
  - **Treasury sets FTP of 50 bps = 5-year TLP**; bank actually funds at Libor+10 in 0-12 month range; this can be incorporated in FTP grid or assumed always spread over Libor and adjusted quarterly/semi-annually
- **Key insight on FTP curve shape**: longer the tenor mismatch, greater the FTP that should be charged; but beyond a material term (say 5 years), incremental liquidity stress per additional year becomes minor; therefore FTP curve does **not** need to follow market yield curve completely beyond 5 years — can be reasonably flat beyond 5 years, certainly flat beyond 10 years
- **Table 15.4**: Hypothetical initial FTP curve (positively sloping, follows market yield curve):
  - 0–6mo=0, 7–12mo=5, 1–2yr=15, 3yr=35, 4yr=40, 5yr=50, 6yr=60, 7yr=70, 8yr=80, 9yr=90, 10yr=100, >10yr=135
- **Table 15.5**: Hypothetical FTP curve with adjustment after 5-year tenor (flattens after 5yr):
  - 0–6mo=0, 7–12mo=5, 1–2yr=15, 3yr=35, 4yr=40, 5yr=50, 6yr=51, 7yr=52, 8yr=53, 9yr=54, 10yr=55, >10yr=60
- **Paradox noted**: in stable market, if always able to rollover, gap length is immaterial; in liquidity crisis, gap length is also immaterial (any gap is fatal — bank must go to central bank lender of last resort). UK FSA focuses on 2-week and 90-day funding gap as assumed critical periods; Basel III focuses on 30-day gap (assumes crisis won't last >30 days — "somewhat unrealistically")
- Note: assumption that one can always rollover funding drove emergence of structured finance vehicles (funding arbitrage ABCP conduits, SIVs); SIVs suffered extinction during 2007–2008; ABCP was "hors de combat" for a period

### Proxies for the Funding Liquidity Premium (pp. 868-870)
- Internal funds price = cost of liquidity for the bank = additional borrowing costs for raising longer term funds, chargeable solely for liquidity reasons; must strip out credit risk element from all-in borrowing cost — not straightforward
- Base case: bank accessing wholesale at Libor-flat across entire term structure → FTP could be Libor-flat; but this is current state only; zero FTP justified only on match-funded basis
- For large bank: primary issuance level in stable market lies above secondary market level
- **CEBS document suggests 4 proxy measures**:
  1. Risk-free curve + CDS spread
  2. Risk-free rate + maturity liquidity premium + institution liquidity premium + buffer premium
  3. Direct funding cost + term premium + buffer premium
  4. Short-term financing cost + term funding cost (including contingent liabilities)
- **Author's recommended proxies**:
  1. Difference between funded rate and unfunded rate for the bank (swap rate vs bond asset-swap spread at same tenor)
  2. Difference between risk-free rate and swap rate (price of general bank risk plus liquidity)
  3. Difference between: (a) paying fixed on term IRS and (b) paying fixed on same-tenor money market swap or OIS swap — implicit measure of TLP
  4. Incremental increase in bank's COF for each additional tenor step; e.g.: 1yr=20 bps, 2yr=30, 3yr=35, 4yr=40, 5yr=50 — take increase at each tenor point as liquidity premium (credit risk element theoretically almost identical at each step)
  5. Difference between bank's CDS spread and asset-swap spread (ASW) — the CDS basis; theoretically represents liquidity premium vs pure credit risk; however due to other factors driving CDS, should not be used in isolation
- **Recommendation**: base FTP charge on average of all of the above; no transparent explicit cost of liquidity — element of judgement always required

#### Example 15.3: Sample Policy Guidance — The Liquidity Premium (p. 870)
- FTP reviewed every 6 months; approaches for TLP proxies:
  1. Difference between ASW and CDS of bank (where negative) for each tenor maturity
  2. Difference between funding spread of bank of same credit rating or peer-group bank
  3. Difference between fixed rate on term swap and fixed rate on OIS swap of same tenor
  - Additionally: secondary market yields less primary market yields; where no liquid secondary market, spread differential between 2-year and longer tenor recent issuances; previous 5-year issuance vs new 5-year issue today; subjective add-on based on ALCO belief about future longer-term funding cost
  - All inputs feed into FTP calculation

### Template Funds Transfer Pricing Document (pp. 871-872)
- Implementing FTP policy that explicitly charges business lines for liquidity cost faces inertia and resistance from business lines (particularly if historically paid Libor-flat or Libor+fixed spread)
- FTP policy should always be owned by the Board, delegated to ALCO, implemented by Finance department
- Template FTP policy available on Wiley website supplementary material (see Ch. 19)
- **Example FTP matrix from Wiley template**:
  - Liabilities: <6 months = Libor; 6-12 months = Libor+10 bps; 1-5 years = Libor+30 bps; >5 years = Libor+50 bps
  - Bank using relatively flat term structure; no bid-offer spread; new 2-year asset attracts same TP charge as new 2-year liability earns
- Additional template policy on Wiley website: cost allocation policy for reserves and non-interest-bearing liabilities (sub-set of FTP policy)

#### Chapter 15 References
- Gregory, J. (2009), *Counterparty Credit Risk: The New Challenge for Financial Markets*, Wiley
- Hull, J. and White, A. (2011), *CVA and Wrong Way Risk*, Working Paper, Rotman School of Management
- Picault, E. (2005), "Calculating and Hedging Exposure, CVA and Economic Capital for Counterparty Credit Risk," in Pykhtin (ed.), *Counterparty Credit Risk Modelling*, RISK Books

